Lecture 12.2:Reproduction andDevelopment

BMEN920002

Jordan Chambers

jordanc@unimelb.edu.au

Learning objectives

  • Describe male hormones and hormonal control of male reproduction
  • Describe female hormones and hormonal control of female reproduction
  • To understand spermatogenesis and oogenesis
  • Describe fertilization and embryonic development
  • To understand aging and senescence
  • Suggestedreading
    • Saladin, Anatomy & Physiology: The Unity of Form and Function 9e
      • 27.1, 27.3, 27.4
      • 28.2, 28.3
      • 29.1-29.4

The two sexes

  • In sexual reproduction, the offspring receives genes from two parents
    • The parents produce gametes and meet and combine theirgenes in a zygote
    • Requires motility and nutrients
      • Two kinds of gametes: A small motile one (sperm) and large nutrient-laden one (egg or ovum)
  • In sexually reproducing species, females produce eggs and males produce sperm
    • In humans, we also have genetic definitions where the presence of Y sex chromosome is classified asmale
  • The sex of a child is determined at conception
    • But sexual differentiation occurs 5-6 week embryo
      • The gene SRY produces testis-determining factor, which interacts with other genes to produceandrogen receptors and initiate development of the male anatomy
      • It is a absence or presence of androgens that determines the sexual differentiation

Figure 27.2

Male hormones

  • The two androgens are testosterone and dihydrotestosterone
  • Puberty starts with secretion of pituitary gonadotropin
    • Testosterone stimulates growth of the sex organs, sperm production, generalised body growth andbrain/libido
    • Dihydrotestosterone stimulates hair, skin and apocrine glands
  • Testosterone levels peak around the age of 20 and steadily decline to as little as one-fifth of this by age80
    • There is corresponding decline in secretory activity, sperm production and libido
    • There is also a decrease in negative inhibition of the pituitary, so higher levels of follicle-stimulatinghormone and luteinizing hormone

Hormonal control ofmalereproductivefunction

  • Luteinizing hormone stimulatesinterstitial endocrine cells to secreteandrogens
  • Follicle-stimulating hormone stimulatesthe nurse cells to secrete androgen-binding protein, which binds andaccumulates testosterone inseminiferous tubules and epididymis
  • Inhibin is also secreted by nurse cells,which selectively suppress the secretionof FSH by the pituitary

Femalehormones

  • Female hormones include oestrogen, progesterone and prolactin
    • Estrogens include oestradiol, oestriol and oestrone
  • Puberty starts thelarche followed by pubarche and menarche
    • Largely controlled by GnRH, FSH and LH (similar to males)
    • Can be delayed due to body fat below 17-22% (required for pregnancy and lactation)
    • FSH stimulates development of ovarian follicles and induces secretion of oestrogens, progesterone,inhibin and small amounts of androgens
    • Oestradiol stimulates ovaries and sex organs, height, widening of the hips, fat deposition andthickening of the sick
  • Females go through midlife change in hormone secretion called climacteric, which is accompanied bymenopause
    • Does not start at a specific age, but when approximately 1000 follicles left

Hormonal control offemalereproductivefunction

  • The sexual cycle consists of the ovarian cycle andthe menstrual cycle
  • Ovarian cycle
    • Follicular phase
      • FSH stimulates continued growth of allfollicles in the cohort and the secretion ofoestradiol (causing dominant follicleupregulates receptors)
      • Oestradiol inhibits GnRH, which decreasesFSH and increases LH
        • Antral follicles degenerate
    • Luteal phase
      • LH stimulates oestradiol and progesterone
      • If pregnancy doesnt occur, corpus luteumundergoes to involution
      • FSH begins to rise, as ovarian steroidsecretion decreases

Hormonal control offemalereproductivefunction

  • Menstrual cycle
    • In proliferative phase endometrial tissue isrebuilt, stimulated by oestradiol
    • In the secretory phase, endometrial glandssecrete glycogen, stimulated by progesterone
    • In the premenstrual phase, the drop inprogesterone contracts spiral arteries of theendometrium
      • The lack of blood flow causes death ofendometrial tissue and arterial spasms inthe myometrium
    • Menstrual phase involves discharge ofmenstrual fluid (endometrium, blood andserous fluid)

Fertilization

  • Acrosomalreaction involves the exocytosis ofenzymes that digest the granulosa cells and thezona
  • Fertilization combines two haploids to form adiploid
  • The binding of sperm to the egg prevents furtherfertilization by
    • Opening sodium channels in the egg membrane
    • Sperm penetration allows calcium inflow, whichstimulates the cortical granules to release theirsecretion
      • Secretion swells with water

Congenital anomaly

  • An abnormal structure or position
  • Teratogens
    • Drugs, chemical, infectious diseases, radiation
    • Effect depends on genetic susceptibility, dosage and stage of development
  • Mutagens and genetic anomalies

Aging and senescence

  • Senescence is the degeneration that occurs in an organ system and includes
    • Gradual loss of reserve capacities
    • Reduce ability to repair damage
    • Increased susceptibility to disease
  • Organ systems dont all degenerate at the same rate
  • Integumentary system (loss of elastic fibres, fewer blood vessel)
  • Skeletal system (osteoblasts become less active and less protein synthesis)
  • Muscular system (myofibrils are smaller weaker, sarcomeres disorganised, mitochondria)
  • Nervous system (loses mass, fewer synapses, reduced synaptic transmission, slower conduction)
  • Sense organs
  • Endocrine system (reproductive, growth and thyroid hormone levels drop, pineal gland becomes calcified)
  • Circulatory system (multiple, complicated effects)

Aging and senescence

  • Immune system (amounts of tissue, decrease in hematopoietic stem cells)
  • Respiratory system (reduce cartilage, elastic tissue and alveoli)
  • Urinary system (number of functioning nephrons)
  • Digestive system (less secretions, atrophy of epithelium and muscle)
  • Reproductive system (more gradual for men, more pronounced rapid for women, mainly hormonesecretion)
